{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_melville_ver02/data/sn84026749/0022225405A/1923120601/0415.xml":{"full_text":"COMMUNIST PLOT TO BURN BRITISH BALLOT BOXES IS ALLEGED\nBIOTS ALSO\nBLAMED\nON BEDS\nOrders Came From Moscow,\nCharge-Women As Problem\nr In Election.\nBy DAVID M. CHURCH,\nInternational New* Service.\nLONDON, Pec. 6.\u2014The first\nserious disorder in the British gen\neral election today was reported\nfrom Belfast, where Daniel Brad\nley was shot during a fight. In\nmost places polling had proceeded\nquietly up to this afternoon. Fa\nvorable weather indicated that a\nheavy vote would be east, espe\ncially on the part of Great\nBritain\u2019s 7,000,000 enfranchised\nwomen.\nAccording to the Daily Mail\ncommunists organised a pl\u00dft to\nupset the election by burning bal\nlot boxes, cutting off the lights in\nvoting places and slashing the\ntires of motor cars carrying anti\ns communist voters to the polls.\nExpect 20,M0,000 Votes.\nThe brevity of Premier Baldwin\u2019s\nfinal appeal to the voters caused\nmuch surprise. He merely asked\nsupport \u201cin the fight against unem\nployment.\u201d\nIt was estimated that about\n10,000,000 ballots would be cast.\nThe women are an unknown fac\ntor, making it difficult to forecast\nthe outcome. Although a sensa\ntional upset is possible, betting\nodds favored the return of the Tory\nparty with a slight majority in the\nHouse of Commons. It is highly\nQuestionable whether the Tories\nwill have a sufficient majority to\nput through Premier Stanley Bald\nwin\u2019s measure for a protective\ntariff.\nOn account of the widespread dis\norders which marked the end of the\ncampaign special instructions were\nissued to the London police.\nIt was reported that Scotland\nYard had discovered a plot to intim-\nMate women voters and keep i\nw them away from the polls.\nCharges Moscow Plot.\nThe Evening News charged that\nthe \u201celection plots-\u2019 were prompt\ned by Moscow.\nInternational issues have played\nan important part in the election\nbattle. The Liberals promised to\nsupport the League of Nations if\nreturned to power The Laborites\npledged themselves to work for re\nvision of the Versailles treaty if\nthey are voted into office.\nThree big issues stand out in to\nday\u2019s election, namely: Unemploy\nment, tariff protection and capital\nThe Conservative party, the gov\nerning party, goes to the polls upon\na platform in favor of a prot active\ntariff. Prime Minister Stanley Bald\nwin and his supporters maintaining\nthat a protective tariff is needed 1o\nprotect British trade and to end un\nemployment.\nThe reunited Liberal party, under\ng the leadership of the two ex\npremiers, Asquith and Lloyd George,\nIs opposing the Conservative party\nwith a platform in favor of free\ntrade, the Liberals maintaining that\nprotection will increase the cost of\nliving and will not end unemploy\nment. The Liberals are also de\nmanding a more active foreign\npolicy and greater efforts to end\nthe unsettled European conditions\ndue to the reparations problem.\nThe Labor party is seeking votes\non a platform that demands a\ncapital levy upon all fortunes of\n<25,000 or over, for the payment of\nwar debts. The Labor j>arty also\ndemands great national steps for\nthe relief of unemployment and a\nforeign policy that will provide for\nrevision of the Treaty of Versailles.\nPersonalities Stano Out.\nBoth the Conservatives and the\nLiberals are making onslaughts\nagainst the Labor party on grounds\nthat the proposed capital levy is\na socialistic confiscation of private\nproperty.\nThree great personalities stand\nout in today's election \u2014Stanley\nr Baldwin, H. H. Asquith and Llojd\nGeorge.\nBaldwin has forced an unpopular\nelection and stands in a faLg, way\nto lose some of his power ir he is\nnot voted out of office altogether.\nAsquith and Lloyd George, after\na feud of several years* standing,\nare again fighting side by side for\nYou don\u2019t need as\nmuch ice' in .Winter,\nbut you need it just\nas much\u2014\nAuthorities on food and its\ncare will tell you that food\nsubjected to sudden changes\nin temperature spoils quickly.\nOften, even though it is not\n\u201cspoiled\u201d, it has undergone\nchemical changes that make it\nunhealthful.\nThe clean, safe, healthful place for\nperishable foods is your refriger\nator, kept at an even temperature\nby a regular supply of ice.\nAMERICAN\nICE\ni COMPANY\nPresident\u2019s Message\nWas Dictated by Him\nBy WILLIAM HARD.\nPresident Coolidge\u2019s message to Congress today will be\nto the country an illustration of the man as well as a dis\ncourse on. national policies.\nIt happens that this message differs from many previous\nPresidential messages in previous Administrations in\nthat virtually from beginning to end it is entirely the Presi\ndent\u2019s own composition in the President\u2019s own words.\nMany previous Presidents have-*\nthankfully received large passages\nof their messages from intimate\nadvisers and even from casual con\ntributors who happened to think\nthat a certain thing would be a\ngood thing to say and who happened\nt<? be friendly enough or forward\nenough to send it to the President.\nSome presidential messages have\nbeen like a long freight train with\nall sorts of cars contributed from\nall sorts of origins and Simply\nhitched together behind one loco\nmotive with their original freight\nstill in them.\nMethod Highly Different.\nPresident Coolidge\u2019s method of\naccumulating a message is highly\ndifferent. From authoritative in\nformation it may be described as\nfollows:\nFirst the President listens to an\nendless multitude of callers; and he\nvirtually never has any real desire\nto have them give him their ideas\nin writing. He prefers simply to\nlisten. It is thought that perhaps\nin the period of time since he be\ncame President he has listened to a\nlarger number of words than any\nother President in any equal num\nber of months.\nRoosevelt is the only other Presi\ndent who perhaps in that same\nnumber of months ever received so\nmany guests at the White House;\nbut, since Rosevelt spent so much\nof the time saying words to the\nguests, it is regarded here as cer\ntain that Coolidge\u2014day for day\nand month for month \u2014has listened\nto more words than even Roose\nvelt himself.\nThat is the first stage in Cool\nidge\u2019s writing of a message. The\nsecond stage is dumb mediation.\nThe President usually cannot\nPJfILEY DI M\nPH NDT YH\nENDED\nConference With N. Y. Central\nto Be Followed by Meeting\nWith Other Lines.\nBy International News Service.\nNEW YORK, Dec. S.\u2014 Railroad\nBrotherhood officials, representing\nengineers and firemen, hoped to\nconclude their wage conference\nwith heads of the New York Cen\ntral lines late today, it was stated\nby Warren Stone, chief of the\nBrotherhood of Locomotive Engi\nneers.\nStone said this morning that the\nworkers and employers had not\nreached a definite agreement. He\nsaid the present conference was\nto be followed by meetings with\nthe heads of other railroads and\nthat it would be several weeks be\nfore the negotiations were ended.\nRepresentatives of the conductors\nand trainmen will meet with the\nNew Ybrk Central chiefs Friday,\npresenting their demands for a\nwage Increase.\nThe present conferences are pre\nliminary to a final settlement.\nStone said. They are being held\nbehind closed doors.\nFailure of negotiations will re\nsult in their presentation to the\nUnited States Railroad Labor\nBoard.\na return to power which they have\nlost. The elections are bound to\nincrease the power of these two\nmen, even if they do not regain\ncontrol of the government.\nIn the background, an unknown\nquantity, stand Ramsay MacDonald\nand his Labor cohorts. No one can\nsay just how Labor will fare In\nthis contest. In the last election\nLabor made surprising strides and\nbecame of the party* of the opposi\ntion. If Labor makes equal prog\nress in this election there is a\nchance of Labor coming into con\ntrol of the Government.\nOn the other hand, the Labor\nparty in this election has to face\na re-united Liberal party, and there\nis a possibility that the Liberals,\nwhose votes were split in the last\nelection, may take sufficient seats\naway from Labor to depose that\nparty from its place as chief op\nposition of the government.\nElections Are Tricky.\nhen polling started the\nstrength of the contending parties\nin Parliament was as follows:\nConservatives, 332; Labor, 144; I\nLiberals, 117; Ulsterites, 11, and\nothers, 8.\nIf the Liberals and Labor c-jm\nh\u00a3ned seats away from\nthe CoiXsrvatlves it will mean that.\nStanley Baldwin will have an un\nworkable majority in Commons and\nwill not be able to carry out his\nprotectionist program Further in\nroads would necessitate the forma\ntion of a coalition government.\nEnglish politics is tricky, and ft\nIs never safe to make predictions,\neven on election day, but the best\njudgment of the political seers\nseems to be that the Conservatives\nare going to lose their safe ma\njorlty today, and If ara re*\nturned It will be with an unsafe\nmajority.\nThere Is an even chance that no\nparty will be returned with a safe\nmajority, and a coalition govern\nment will be necessary. If a coali\ntion government comes it is safe\nto venture that Lloyd George will\nenter the cabinet either as foreign\nsecretary or as chancellor of the\nexchequer.\nThere are no signs of any de\ncisive result in today\u2019s poll. An\nother election within eighteen\nmonths is practically certain.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES TA< National THURSDAY, DECEMBER B, 1928.\n4\nbegin his writing on any given topic\nuntil he has got that topic all\nthought through. He does not be\ngin and then change the words and\nthen begin all over again. He seems\nunable to start at all until his\nthought is complete. Until that\nmoment he sits speechless and un\nable to find a word to say.\nRapid at Dictation.\nThen comes the third and last\nstage. He starts dictating. It hap\npens that he does not scribble his\nown manuscript at all; and it\nhappens that-\u2014unlike President Wil\n-BOJ?77^e doe not tap his own type\nwriting machine. He dictates; and\nas soon as he actually starts he\nsays the words off with no hesita\ntion and no meditation whatsoever\nany more.\nHe is slow in starting; t\u2014, rather,\nhe does not start at all till every\nthing in his own mind is settled;\nand then he goes through with all\nthe sentences and all the phrases\nanu all the individual words com\ning along rapid-fire a* if he al\nready knew them by heart.\nThese facts regarding his method\nof composition will be found reflected\nin the message. Severe critics of\nthe policies advocated in the mes\n*ac\u00ae will be found in Congress in\nlarge numbers.\nAdditionally it will be found\nthat the last few words of the mes\nsage will be much ridiculed In Con\ngress for sentimental vagueness.\nOutside of those last fe# words,\nhowever, \u2018the friends and the\ncritics of the President here are\nfor the most part pretty united in\nsaying that this message for a\nsort of ordered and pondered and yet\nfluent clarity of statement deserve*\nquite high rank among Presidential\ncommunications.\n4\nQIBDENTISTS\nTO 8E DRIVEN\nFDOMN.Y.\nState Officially Opens War on\nSwindlers l,OOO in\nMetropolis Alone.\nBy International New* Servic*.\nNEW YORK, Dec. New York\nState today officially opened war\non quack dentists.\nUnder direction of Attorney Gen\neral Carl Sherman, and Dr. Minor\nJ. Terry, secretary of the State\ndental board of examiners, an in\nvestigation of all dentists through\nout the State was begun.\nDr. Terry estimated 1,000 fake\ndentists were operating in New\nYork City and an equal number in\nthe State. Sherman said warrants\nwould be issued for the arrest of\nthese men.\nDr. Terry declared the fake\ndentists were not \u201cgraduates\u201d of a\n\u201cdiploma mill,\u201d but operated with\nout even this formality.\n\u201cMany are barbers, laborers and\nclerks, without so much as a com\n61ete common school education,\u201d\n\u00bbr. Terry said. \"They purchase a\nfew dental tools and rent an of\nfice. They Calk prospective patients\ninto paying a heavy advance fee,\ngive them fake treatments and then\nsuddenly move away.\u201d\nSome patients have died from\nthese treatments, Dr. Tarry de\nclared.\nDOGTORSIOSE\nSESSION WITH\nBANQUET\nSongs and Dances Add to\nMerriment of D. C., Va., and\nMd. Medical Men.\nMerriment marked the closing of\nthe fall meeting and dinner of the\nMedical Society of Virginia, Mary-\nI land, and the District of Columbia,\nin the Arlington Hotel, yesterday.\nThe forenoon was devoted to a\nscientific discussion of human dis\nease* and progress In medicine.\nSpeakers were Dr. Thomas M.\nFoley, Dr. Custis Lee Hall, Dr.\nEdmund Horgan, Dr. J. A. Gannon,\nDr. J. Russell Verbrycke, James\nA. Cahill, jr\u201e and Dr. William B.\nMarbury.\nA dinner and entertainment in\nthe ball room of the hotel followed\nthe meeting. The program included\nMrs. Ida Clarke, singer and ac\ncord eoni\u00abt, assisted by Master Billy\nClarke, with drum and traps;\nGeorge O\u2019Connor, in songs, accom\npanied by Matt Horne; Miss Ca\nmille Little. dancer; Ralph Dela\nvergne, singe f Miss Estelle Murray\nand Royal Foster, in the -Argentine\ntango, \u2018and Marguerite Agniei,\ndancer, accompanied by the Amplco.\nThe Washington Canoe Club orches\ntra played throughout the enter\ntainment.#\nThe program was arranged un\nder the direction of Dr, A. M. Mc-\nDonald and Dr. Joseph D. Rogers,\nassisted by Charles Waters.\nTDEIGHT SUING\nIS MH\nBYI.C.C.\nShippers Gain Half Billion by\nReduction Made Last July,\nIs Report.\nBy International New, Service.\nThe freight bill of American ship\npers will be more than half a billion\ndollars less this year than it was last\nyear because of the 10 per cent rate\nreduction ordered by the Interstate\nCommerce Commission July 1, 1923,\naccording to an estimate made today\nby the commission in its annual re\nport to Congress.\nIn order to give the new rates a\ntrial, the commission stated, no fur\nther general investigation of rates\nhas been made. The commission\npointed to three noteworthy facts\nin the country\u2019s transportation his\ntory during the current year. These\nqre:\nVolume Seto Record.\nThe unprecedented volume of traf\nfic handled.\nThe concurrent transformation of\na car shortage condition into one of\ncar\nAn exceptionally equitable distri\nbution of available equipment over\nterritory in which the large traffic\nmovements originate.\nThe report called Attention to the\nfact that the railroads handled more\nfreigh traffic during the first niua\nmonths of 1823 than during any pre\nvious corresponding period, the net\nton-mlles of revenue aqd nonrevenue\nfreight being reptorted as 848,796,799.-\n000. This represents an increase of\n2.9 per cent over the same period of\n1920, which was the previous high\nmark.\nNet Earnings Grow.\n\"The marked business revival of\n1923 has greatly'augmented both the\ngross and net earnings of the car\nriers as compared with the earnings\nin- the depressed years, .1921 and\n1922, the report said.\n\u201cIn the calendar year 1921 the\noperating revenues of class 1 steam\nroads amounted to $5,573,158,138,\nand that net railway operating in\ncome, which is the amount from\nwhich fixed charges and dividends\nare paid, was $616,945,814. In 1922,\nin spite of strike troubles and the\nrate reductions effective in the mid\ndle of the year, the operating reve\nnues increased to $6,617,252,656, and\nthe net operating income to $776,-\n865, 960.\nThe improvement in the net earn\nings of the carriers has by no me&us\nbeen equally distributed among the\nindividual systems. The recovery\nfrom the depression of 1921 was more\nmarked in the eastern and southern\ndistricts than in the western dis\ntrict.\u201d\nMany Serious Accidents.\nDuring the year ended June 30,\n1923, there were 119 collisions and\nderailments, in which 285 persons\nwere killed and 1,785 injured.\n\"The need for continued effort to\nprevent railway accidents with their\ngreat loss of life, injury to persons\nand destruction of property can\nhardly be overstated,\u201d the report\nsaid.\nUH DH\n111\nSIAHTED\nTrash Cans to Be Placed at\nCentral Points, Women\nAre Told.\nCLARENDON, Va., Dec. 6.\u2014At\nthe meeting of the Clarendon\nWoman\u2019s Civic Club, held yesterday\nin the Community Hall, it was re\nported that trash cans will be\nplaced in the central park of Clar\nendon.\nThe club women met last Satur\nday at Clarendon station and\nopened a clean-up campaign. Mer\nchants of Clarendon are requested\nto place all trash in the cans to\nassist the club in keeping the town\nclean.\nHarold Byroads, of Fox Station,\nArlington county, arrested on a\ncharge of destroying the property\nof the Columbus Country Cldb at\nFort Berry, Va., will be tried be\nfore Police Judge Harry R. Thomas\ntoday.\nIt was learned at the jail last\nnight that a thorough investigation\nis now going on by the officials of\nArlington county, and who are be\nj ing aided by the members of the\nKnights of Columbus Club.\nThe arrest of Byroads, who is\nseventeen years old, is the first\nthat has been made, and officers at\nthe jail last night said that others\nare expected in the next few days.\nThe property said to be worth\nabout $50,000 is now a wreck.\nCarl Steger, of Radnor Heigh taf\nArlington county, arrested by Dep\nuty Sheriff James D. East, charged\nwith selling whiskey to a minor,\nwas given a hearing yesterday and\nheld for the action of the grand\njury.\nAnnouncement was made last\nnight that the Presbyterians who\nrecently organized in Clarendon will\nhold their first service on Sunday\nDecember 9, at 3:80 o\u2019clock.\nThe services will be held In the\nbuilding now being used by the\nClarendon Methodist Church.\nClarendon Rebekah Lodge, No.\n28, will hold a bazaar for the bene\nfit of the regalia fund, in Clarendon\nCommunity Hall on Friday and\nSaturday. a feature for Saturday\nwill be the personal appearance of\nBanta, Claus, who has Invited all\ndf the children of the community\nto visit him.\nI Each evening there will be\ndancing between the hour* of 10\nand 12.\nDRIVE IS ON FOR\nT BUILDING\nFUNDS\n$40,000 Sought to Remodel\nTwelfth Street Branch of\nAssociation.\nA city-wide campaign to raise\n$46,000 for ths remodeling of the\nTwelfth street branch of the Young\nMen\u2019s Christian Association was\nlaunched today,' a force of 200 be\nginning the work of canvassing the\ncity undeV direction of J. L. Moor\nland.\nThe campaign committee includes\nJ. Percy Bond, Dr. J. Hayden John\nson, Dr. A. M. Curtis, Dr. C. H.\nMarshall, George H. Murray and\nEmmet J. Scott, treasurer of How\nard University.\nThe building wee erected twenty\nyears ago. The fund now being\nraised will be used to provide a\ncafeteria and a toys\u2019 department\non the first floor, a library, bil\nliard and pool room on the second\ntiooi- and an assembly hall and dor\nmitory alterations on the fourth\nand fifth floors. The swimming\n,pooi will also be remodeled.\nThe campaign force is divided\ninto teams of ten men each, under\nthe following team captains: John\nP. Atkinson, William I. Barnes,\nCharles Booker, E. N. Broadnax,\nFrank Coleman, Rupert B. Clark,\nDr. W. O. Claytor, Simeon Cunning\nham. Victor R. Daly, Robert D.\nEvans, Thornton M. Hunt, Charles\nH. Flagg, Thomas Frazier, Jesse Fos\nter, Dr. U. L. Houston. George A\nParker and R. C. Wilks.\ncmkhswebs\nMi\nCENSURE\nComptroller Holds Remittal of\nSentence as Unqualified\nPardon.\nBy Interaattenal New* Scpvtee.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 6. \u2014Comptrol-\nler Charles Craig, of Now York\ncity, today awaited delivery of of\nficial order of President Coolidge,\nremitting his slxty-day sentence,\nImposed by Federal Judge Mayer\nfor contempt of court before fram\ning his reply. The Comptroller was\ninformed of the order over the tele\nphone from Washington last night.\nCraig took the attitude that the\nremission was an \u201cunconditional\nand unqualified pardon.\u201d He issued\na vitriolic statement, attacking At\ntorney General Daugherty, who\nmade a report to President Cool\nidge In connection with the case.\n\u201cAttorney General Daugherty\u2019s\nreport is a confession accompanied\nby cries, groans and squawks in\ntended to mislead the public as to\nIts true character,\u201d Craig said,\n\u201cContrary to all the statements of\nDaugherty the document Is an un\nconditional and unqualified pardon.\"\nCraig accused Daugherty of ad\nvising the President to \u201cbe above\nthe law,\u201d and added that the At\ntorneys General action \u201csavors of\npolitical cowardice.\u201d\nTHE ORANGE GROVE\nj, \u00bbil|i| |9|\nx\niMMhSKb^BWml^^PKkm^l^^ ImI W r vML 3F wOl\nRUMlK\u00a3^MQ\u00dfflKiGr^&^F^ muM I\u00bb& W v\nNow Open\nS. W. Comer 12th and New York Ave. N. W.\nOperated by the same American boys that were on 9th street last winter. We are not connected with\nany other store in this city. The quality of our fruit is seldom equaled and never excelled.\nI I I I I 1.l \u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0l *ll\nORANGES GRAPEFRUIT\nPer dozen 25c 3,4, 5 and 6 for. 25c\n50 .in basketsl.oo 13, 16, 20 and 25 in Basket for. ..SI.OO\nMIXED BASKETS\u2014ORANGES AND GRAPEFRUIT. .SI.OO\nTAKE YOUR CHOICE ANY BASKET IN THE HOUSE. .SI.OO\n,Tm H. B. CORLEY, Mgr.\u2014TWK ,T? S S\nPOLICEMAN HAS BEEN\nON BEAT 60 YEARS\n\nFor nearly sixty years has \"Capt.\u201d Richard Hamilton Cook been\na member of the police department. During that time he has had\nabout 100 days leave and the rest of the time he has put in guard*\ning Washingtonians. Captain Cook patrols the grounds of the\nUnited States Department of Agriculture, to which job he was\nappointed by* Abraham Lincoln. The Captain has not had a day\noff in twenty-five yean.\nHOUSE TAKES UP\nCOMMITTEE\nLISTS\nLittle Legislation Before Xmas\nExpected\u2014New Members\n\u201cRolling Logs.\u201d\nThe House will dispatch little legis\nlation before the Christmas holidays.\nImmediately after hearing Presi\ndent Coolidge today and referring\nhis message with its recommenda\ntions to appropriate committees, the\nHouse started upon a program of\nthree-day recesses until its commit\ntees are selected and organized.\nAfter the committees are named they\nwill require time to consider and re\nport bills to the House.\nThe Republican committee on com\nmittees will meet tomorrow to begin\nits task of assigning Republican\nmembers of the House to various\ncommittees. This is a job requiring\ntime, patience and the exercise of\nmuch judgment and political (acu-\nmen. The log-rolling arid trading for\ncommittee placement engage the a-v\n--tivities of Congressmen at the open\ning of all new Congresses to the ex\nclusion of all other matters. It is\nnow tn its most active stage.\nThe committees to be Tilled first\nwill be those on Appropriations, Ac\ncounts, Rules and Ways and Means.\nThere is immediate work ahead of\neach of these committees. Chair\nman Madden,\u201dof the Appropriations\nCommittee, desires to start work at\nonce on the twelve or. thirteen supoly\nbills for the next fiscal year, which\nwill have right of way in the House\nand must be law before June 30,\nnext.\nOther committees will be filled as\nrapidly as the Committee on Com\nmittees can make their selections.\nThe Democrats are anxious to have\nthe Ways and Means Committee\nmembership made up because their\nmembers of the committee act as a\ncommittee on committees in placing\nDemocrats on House leommittees.\nThe Rules Committee must begin at\nonce a revision of the House rqles.\nwidovTof police chief\nKILLS SELF WITH GAS\nYORK, Pa., Dec. 6.\u2014Mrs. Nora\nBush, widow of Chief of Police\nCharles A. committed suicide\nat her home here. The woman had\nbeen despondent since the death of\nher husband. She committed the\ndeed by inhaling gas from a tube.\n0. C. POLICEMAN\nAPPOINTED 81\nLINCOLN\n4\nHas Been In Service Sincfcn\nWith but 100 Days Total\nof Vacations.\nBy WILLIAM PICKETT HELM.\nHere is \u201cCaptain\u201d Richard Hamil.\nton Cook, of Washington, D. CL, the\noldest active policeman, in point of\nservice, in the United States. He\nhas been on duty for nearly sixty\nconsercutive years, and during that\ntime has. taken less than 100 dayd*\nvacation. Now he is preparing te\ntake some real time off\u2014a solid\nmonth of hunting.\n\u201cCaptain\u201d Cook patrols the\ngrounds of the United States De.\npartmsnt of Agriculture at Wash,\nington. He received his appoint,\nment from Abraham Lincoln, t*\nJanuary, 1864, as a reward fog\nheroic service in the army, from\nwhich he had been discharged two\ndays before.\nIt has been twenty-five years\nsince \u201cCaptain\u201d Cook has had such\na vacation* During the interval\nhe has taken only one or two days\noff at a .tme. He had one other\nlong vacation, however\u2014and that\nwas forced upon him\u2014back in 1866,\nwhen he was suspended from duty\non a trumped-up charge. Ho stlfl\ncarries in his wallet an order\u00bb\nsigned by President Johnson de\nmanding his reinstatement.\nFor several years past, \u201cCaptain\u201d\nCook has not made an arrest. He\nis perfectly able to do it, but there\nis no longer any disorder on his\nbeat. His main trouble is with\nautomobllists who go the wrong way\non one-way drives. He overhauls\nthem on his bicycle and puts them\nright.\nThe present Secretary of Agrleul\ntore is' the thirteenth over whose\nsafety \"Captain\u201d Cook has stood\nguard*\n(Copyright. 1913. WfUtam Piekett Hehn.l\nFATHER COMMITS SUICIDE\nWHILE MENDING UMBRELLA\nPHOENIXVILLE, Pa.' Dec. *B.\u2014Jo\nseph Monarek committed suicide\nWhile mending an umbrella. When\ntwo of his children returned from\nschool they found their father had\nstrangled himself with a strap.\nHe was on the floor, with ths\nbroken strap around his neck. Mrs.\nMonarek was out working and ths\nman was alone in the house. He\nhad been sick and unable to work\nfor about two years.\nDAMAGE SUIT AGAINST\nPOLICEMAN DISMISSED\nChief Justice McCoy, the Dis.\ntrict Supreme Court, yesterday dis*\nmissed a suit for, $25,000 damages\nfiled by William Green, colored,\nagainst Detective Thomas O\u2019Don\nnell and the late Policeman Fred\nerick O. Stange, of the Fourth\nprecinct.\nThe Plaintiff charged that he\nhad been beaten in an alleged un\nlawful raid on Ids home at 1282\nUnion street southwest. Green\nfailed to appear to prosecute the\ncase.\nXMAS CARDS\nBOOKS\nPaul Pearlman\n1711 G St. N. W.\n3","height":"26862","width":"22332"}}
